    "Party_Details": {
      "Role": "Plaintiff",
      "Name": "ABB Installation Materials (East Asia) Pte Ltd",
      "Facts": "The company employed Sher Hock Guan Charles as President and Director from January 1997 to February 2003. During his tenure, he was responsible for the business of low voltage products in South East Asia, South Asia, and Oceania. The company alleged that the defendant owed it express and implied fiduciary and other duties, and that he breached those duties by, among other things, failing to disclose communications with XIHARI and involvement in the establishment of Huadian, assisting a competitor while still employed, and working on business plans for a rival company before resignation.",
      "Issue": "Whether the defendant, as a senior employee and director, owed fiduciary and contractual duties to the plaintiffs and breached those duties by assisting or failing to disclose information about a competitor while still employed.",
      "Rule": "Companies – Directors – Duties; Contract – Contractual terms – Incorporation of terms and conditions found in external document; Alexander v Standard Telephones & Cables Ltd (No 2) [1991] IRLR 286; Canadian Aero Service Ltd v O’Malley (1973) 40 DLR (3d) 371; British Midland Tool v Midland International [2003] EWHC 466; IDC Ltd v Cooley [1972] 1 WLR 443.",
      "Application": "The court found that the defendant, as a director, owed fiduciary duties to the second plaintiff. The court determined that the defendant breached his fiduciary duties by failing to inform the company of XIHARI’s intention to develop and market new circuit breakers, by communicating with Mr Leonhardt to secure his services for XIHARI and Huadian, and by working on business plans for Huadian while still employed. However, the court found insufficient evidence of active participation in other businesses (Great Vision, Xiamen Fu Cheng, Webmoney) during employment.",
      "Conclusion": "Judgment for Plaintiff; damages to be assessed or an account of profits to be taken."
    }
